# 🎯 Resume vs JD Matcher — Pro Version

An advanced AI-powered web app (Streamlit) that goes beyond simple LLM prompting:

## What makes this "advanced" / resume-worthy

| Feature | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| **Hybrid scoring**: LLM judgment + sentence-embedding cosine similarity | Shows you understand both LLM prompting AND classic NLP/ML (embeddings) — interviewers love this combo |
| **Structured JSON output** from LLM (not free text parsing) | Real production pattern — robust, reliable |
| **Skill-level semantic matching** (radar chart) | Per-skill matching, not just one overall score |
| **SQLite history database** | Shows you can persist data, not just call an API |
| **Batch resume comparison + ranking** | Useful for recruiters comparing multiple candidates |
| **Bullet-point rewriter** | Extra generative feature, practical value |
| **Multi-format support** (PDF, DOCX, TXT) | Handles real-world messy input |

## 🖥️ Still a web app (not mobile)
Runs in browser via Streamlit. Deploy free on Streamlit Community Cloud for a public link — works fine on mobile browsers too.

## Project Structure
```
resume_matcher_pro/
├── app.py                 # Main Streamlit UI (3 tabs)
├── file_parser.py          # PDF/DOCX/TXT text extraction
├── semantic_matcher.py     # Embedding-based similarity (sentence-transformers)
├── llm_analyzer.py         # LLM calls (Groq/OpenAI) with structured JSON output
├── database.py             # SQLite history storage
└── requirements.txt
```

## Setup

### 1. Install dependencies
```bash
pip install -r requirements.txt
```
Note: `sentence-transformers` will download a small model (~80MB) on first run — runs locally, no API cost for this part.

### 2. Set API key (choose one)

**Option A — Free (Groq, recommended for learning):**
```bash
export GROQ_API_KEY="your-groq-key"
```
Get free key: https://console.groq.com/keys

**Option B — OpenAI (paid, slightly higher quality):**
```bash
export OPENAI_API_KEY="your-openai-key"
```

The code auto-detects which key is set and switches model accordingly.

### 3. Run
```bash
streamlit run app.py
```

## How It Works (architecture)

1. **Upload** → `file_parser.py` extracts raw text regardless of format
2. **Semantic Score** → `semantic_matcher.py` encodes resume + JD into embeddings (MiniLM model) and computes cosine similarity — this is a pure ML signal, independent of LLM, so it's a good "second opinion" check
3. **LLM Analysis** → `llm_analyzer.py` sends resume + JD to the LLM asking for structured JSON: match %, skills, suggestions
4. **Skill Radar** → for each key skill the LLM identifies from the JD, we re-run embedding similarity against resume chunks to get a per-skill score → visualized as radar chart
5. **Persistence** → every analysis is saved to SQLite so you (or a recruiter) can review history later
6. **Batch mode** → upload multiple resumes against one JD → get a ranked leaderboard

## 📌 Resume bullet point (use this!)
> "Developed an AI-powered resume screening tool combining LLM-based structured analysis (Groq/OpenAI) with sentence-embedding semantic similarity (Sentence-Transformers), featuring batch candidate ranking, per-skill radar visualization, and persistent analysis history via SQLite."

## Next-level ideas (if you want to go even further)
- Add authentication (multi-user, save per-user history)
- Deploy with a FastAPI backend + React frontend instead of Streamlit (shows full-stack skill)
- Add a vector database (ChromaDB/Pinecone) to match resume against multiple JDs at once
- Add LinkedIn job description scraping (auto-fetch JD from a URL)
- Fine-tune a small classifier on real ATS-rejected resumes to predict pass/fail